  "prompt": "Why doesn't neuroscience play a central role in hiring despite all the advances?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why neuroscience hasn't become central to hiring practices:\n\n1. Ethical concerns\n- Potential discrimination\n- Privacy issues\n- Invasiveness of neurological assessments\n\n2. Technical limitations\n- Brain scans are expensive\n- Complexity of interpreting neural data\n- Limited predictive power of current methods\n\n3. Practical challenges\n- Traditional interview methods are still perceived as effective\n- Resistance to changing established hiring processes\n- Lack of standardized neuroscience-based assessment protocols\n\n4. Complexity of human behavior\n- Cognitive processes are multifaceted\n- Neural patterns don't always directly correlate with job performance\n- Individual variability makes generalized predictions difficult\n\n5. Legal and regulatory barriers\n- Potential violations of employment discrimination laws\n- Uncertainty about using neurological data in hiring decisions\n\n6. Cost-effectiveness\n- Current neuroscience techniques are not yet cost-efficient for widespread hiring\n- Traditional methods remain more economical\n\n7. Limited understanding\n- Neuroscience is still an emerging field\n- Incomplete knowledge about how neural patterns translate to workplace skills\n\nWhile neuroscience offers fascinating insights, these factors currently prevent its widespread adoption in hiring practices. However, research continues, and future advances might change this landscape.",
